Let $\displaystyle g(x,y) = x^{2} + y^{2} -4$ be the constraint
function. We thus need to solve the system of equations given by

\begin{align*}
g(x,y) &= 0\\
\nabla f(x,y) &= \lambda \nabla g(x,y)\end{align*}

Plugging in our values gives

\begin{align*}
x^{2} + y^{2} -4  &= 0\\
(-6xy,6-3y^2-3x^2) &= \lambda (2x,2y)\end{align*}

Expanding the second equation gives the following three equations

\begin{align*}
x^{2} &= 4-y^{2}\\
-6xy &= 2\lambda x\\
6 - 3y^2 - 3x^2 &= 2\lambda y\end{align*}

Substituting the first equation in the third equation gives
$\displaystyle 6 - 3y^2 - 3(4-y^{2}) = 2\lambda y$ which simplifies to

\begin{align*}\displaystyle -6  - 3y^2 + 3y^{2} = 2\lambda y\end{align*}

Reducing gives $\displaystyle -3 = \lambda y$. This tells us that
$\displaystyle \lambda \neq 0$ and thus we can divide by it to get that
$\frac{-3}{\lambda} = y$.

Looking at the second equation from the group of three above gives us
that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
0 = 2\lambda x + 6xy = x(2\lambda + 6y)\end{align*}

\subsubsection{Case 1: \emph{x = 0}}\label{case-1-x-0}

Plugging \emph{x = 0} into $\displaystyle g(x,y)$ gives
$\displaystyle y = \pm 2$.

\subsubsection{Case 2: \emph{x $\neq$ 0}}\label{case-2-x-neq-0}

In this case we divide the equation above by \emph{x} and obtain

$2\lambda = -6y = -6\left(\frac{-3}{\lambda}\right) = \frac{18}{\lambda}$

Solving gives $\lambda = \pm3$. Thus $y = \frac{-3}{\lambda} = \mp 1$.
Plugging these \emph{y} values into $\displaystyle g(x,y)$ gives
$x = \pm \sqrt{3}$.

\subsubsection{Compare function values at all candidate
points}\label{compare-function-values-at-all-candidate-points}

We found the following six solutions:

\begin{align*}\displaystyle (0,-2), (0,2), (-\sqrt{3},-1), (\sqrt{3},-1), (-\sqrt{3},1), (\sqrt{3},1)\end{align*}

Plugging in each of the values gives

\begin{align*}
f(0,2) &= 6(2) - (2)^3 - 3(0)^2(2) = 4\\
f(0,-2) &= 6(-2) - (-2)^3 - 3(0)^2(-2) = -4\\
f(-\sqrt{3},-1) &= 6(-1) - (-1)^3 - 3(-\sqrt{3})^2(-1) = 4\\
f(\sqrt{3},-1) &= 6(-1) - (-1)^3 - 3(\sqrt{3})^2(-1) = 4\\
f(-\sqrt{3},1) &= 6(1) - (1)^3 - 3(-\sqrt{3})^2(1) = -4\\
f(\sqrt{3},1) &= 6(1) - (1)^3 - 3(\sqrt{3})^2(1) = -4\end{align*}

and thus the minimum value is -4 and the maximum value is 4.

